definition.value: A monocarboxylic acid amide that is N,N-diethylprop-2-enamide in which the hydrogen at position 2 is substituted by a cyano group and the hydrogen at the 3E position is substituted by a 3,4-dihydroxy-5-nitrophenyl group.
An aspartic acid derivative having a 3-methyl substituent.
Ethers ROR' where R has a double bond adjacent to the oxygen of the ether linkage.
Enol ethers ROR' where R' has the structure SiR''R'''R''''.
The pyranose form of D-glucosamine 6-phosphate.
Ethers ROR' where R' has the structure SiR''R'''R''''.
An amine RNR'R'' where R has a double bond adjacent to the amine nitrogen.
A proteinogenic amino acid derivative resulting from reaction of L-tryptophan at the amino group or the carboxy group, or from the replacement of any hydrogen of L-tryptophan by a heteroatom.
A non-proteinogenic amino acid derivative resulting from reaction of D-tryptophan  at the amino group or the carboxy group, or from the replacement of any hydrogen of D-tryptophan  by a heteroatom.
A 1-(phosphoribosyl)imidazole having the phospho group at the 5'-position and a carboxyamino group at the 5-position on the imidazole ring.
A compound, usually an anti-bacterial agent or a toxin, which inhibits the synthesis of a protein.
Carbonyl compounds where the C=O bond is conjugated to an alkylidene group.
Imines where the C=N bond is conjugated to an alkylidene group.
A triamine comprising spermidine having a double bond at the 2-position.
Nucleic acid polymers where the residues contain 'locked' deoxyribose units and are linked by phosphodiester bonds. The deoxyribose unit conformation is 'locked' by a 2'-C,4'-C-oxymethylene link.
A nucleic acid residue that contains a 'locked' deoxyribose unit.
An N-(3-aminopropyl)but-2-ene-1,4-diamine having a cis-double bond.
An N-(3-aminopropyl)but-2-ene-1,4-diamine having a trans-double bond.
Nucleic acid polymers where the residues have an acyclic three-carbon propylene glycol phosphodiester backbone.
Glycol nucleic acids with an (R) chiral centre in the glycol backbone. They can be synthetically derived from (R)-(+)-glycidol.
Glycol nucleic acids with an (S) chiral centre in the glycol backbone. They can be synthetically derived from (S)-(+)-glycidol.
Nucleic acids that have threose instead of ribose or deoxyribose in their sugar-phosphate backbones.
Nucleic acids where the sugar-phosphate backbone has been replaced by a neutral polyamide backbone such as N-(2-aminoethyl)glycine units.
A monohydroxyflavanone in which the hydroxy group is located at position 3'.
Any hydroxyflavanone with a hydroxy substituent at position 3' of the phenyl ring.
A dihydroxyflavanone that is flavanone substituted by hydroxy groups at positions 3' and 5' respectively.
The (2S)-enantiomer of dihydrotricetin.
The (2S,3S)-stereoisomer of dihydromyricetin.
A homodetic cyclic tetrapeptide made up from L-alanyl, D-alanyl, L-prolyl and 2-amino-8-oxo-9,10-epoxydecanoyl residues.
